<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-804-870  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 804 870.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Journal of Systems and Software  July 1990 v12 n3 p199(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Prediction and control of ADA software defects. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Compton, B. Terry; Withrow, Carol.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A study of two Ada projects shows that software defects can bepredicted in the development phase.andP;  Of all metrics tested,measures of package size proved to be the best predictors ofdefect densities.andP;  The prediction function derived suggests thatdefect density is very high for small Ada packages, decreasesrapidly to reach a minimum for intermediate-sized packages, andthen rises gradually as package sizes increase.andP;  During the designand coding phases, package sizes can be evaluated against thiscriterion, and such strategies as consolidation, furtherdecomposition, redesigning, or recoding can be considered.andP;  Sincethe study found that packages with system integration and test(SIandamp;T) defects are six times more likely to exhibit postdeliverydefects as those without, a two-phased SIandamp;T is suggested.andO;(Reprinted by permission of the publisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software DesignError AnalysisSoftware MetricsADASoftware ComplexityDefects.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Predelivery percent of errors, source lines of code, and packages.andO;(graph)Total errors versus predicted length of a software package.andO;(graph)Error density functions for all packages and packages with errors.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>